I started with a reshape layer because the dense layer has a requirement with the input format. Then I added four dense layers. 
Three hidden layers with an activation function of 'relu' have 1024, 256 and 64 nodes separately.
The last one is an output layer with an activation function of 'softmax' because the output value consists of ten classes.
The validation accuracy is 77.72%, and the training accuracy is 79.64%, which is quite similar. Thus, the model performs well and is not overfitting.

I referred to the model used in the lab here and slightly changed its parameters. There are six convolutional layers. Every two convolutional layers I added a Maxpooling layer. After every Maxpooling, resolution halved in every dimension. To classify the images, a Dense and Softmax layer was added in the last. Furthermore, Dropout layers and Batchnormalization layers were added to regularize the model.
This model worked very well. The accuracy of validation and training both are high and close to 1. However, it may be overfitting.

Answer 3.1 (2p)¶

The most common misclassification is between 1 and other labels. Most misclassifications involve 1, 3, 4, 7 and 10. 
I visualized the misclassification in class 1. I found that when writing 1 , people do not just draw a vertical line like |, but with a slanting horizontal line. So 1 will be easily misclassified as tilt 7 or 4.
I also visualized in other classes. Some images have a very blurry background. Also, since 10 has two digits, it can easily be considered as another number.

Answer 3.2 (4p)¶

There are six figures for different convolutional layers. This model is useful. As can be seen from the figures, these convolutional layers indeed take the local characteristics of the digits. 
In the first figure, it focuses on relatively low-level features. Then, the latter convolution layer integrates the features of the previous convolution layer to form relatively complex features.
So this can greatly reduce the impact of feature position on classification.
